Consider the simplified form of $f(x)=\frac{x+6}{x}$
\begin{align*}
f(x)&=\frac{1x+6}{1x}=\frac{x+6}{x}\\
\end{align*}
In this simplification process, we see the repeated division of the $r_{k}$ by $(r_{k}+1)$ by the divisor $[-\sum_{i\neq k}\frac{c_{j,k}}{c_{j,0}}]$.
After division, $r_{k}$ becomes $[\frac{-6}{1}r_{k}] -1$.
This means it would simplify to a decrease in the coefficient $[\frac{1}{1}],$ which will eventually end in a right division to $0$.
